Month = {OCT},
Abstract = {In this article, we explore the responses of a group of undergraduate
   mathematics students to tasks that deal with areas, perimeters, volumes,
   and derivatives. The tasks challenge the conventional representations of
   formulas that students are used to from their schooling. Our analysis
   attends to the specific mathematical ideas and ways of reasoning raised
   by students, which supported or hindered their appreciation of an
   unconventional representation. We identify themes that emerged in these
   responses and analyze those via different theoretical lenses-the lens of
   transfer and the lens of aesthetics. We conclude with pedagogical
   recommendations to help learners appreciate the structure of mathematics
   and challenge the resilience of certain conventions.},
