Abstract = {Good stories, literary or mathematical, have the ability to keep the
   reader engaged and wanting for more. However, poorly designed stories
   may also elicit a negative aesthetic reaction and thereby reduce
   engagement. By drawing on literary theory and Dietiker's (For the
   Learning of Mathematics 33(3):14-19, 2013; Educational Studies in
   Mathematics 90(3):285-302, 2015) theoretical framework of mathematical
   stories, this essay conceptualises two aspects of mathematical stories
   that are likely to be perceived by the readers as aesthetic
   deficiencies: mathematical cheap plot tricks and mathematical plot
   holes. Additionally, examples of them are proposed from various areas of
   mathematics curriculum and some ideas of how they can be avoided, so as
   not to hinder engagement, are offered.},
