   inaccurate retrospective idealizations. Such artifacts allow us time to
   process the event, extract the lessons it has for us, and to bring these
   lessons to bear on our practices. I offer my own narrative here, as a
   practitioner and researcher, of daily experiences of teaching
   mathematics in the USA during the SARS-CoV-2 pandemic. Sudden
   perturbations to our regular educational practices expose ways in which
