Pages = {351-367},
Month = {JUL},
Abstract = {The article reports aspects of the evolution of a teaching approach over
   repeated trials for beginning symbolic algebra. The teaching approach
   emphasized the structural similarity between arithmetic and algebraic
   expressions and aimed at supporting students in making a transition from
   arithmetic to beginning algebra. The study was conducted with grade 6
   students over 2 years. Thirty-one students were followed for a year, and
   data were analysed as they participated in the three trials conducted
   that year. Analysis of students' written and interview responses as the
   approach evolved revealed the potential of the approach in creating
   meaning for symbolic transformations in the context of both arithmetic
   and algebra as well as making connections between arithmetic and
   symbolic algebra. Students by the end of the trials learnt to use their
   understanding of both procedures and a sense of structure of expressions
   to evaluate/simplify expressions and reason about equality/equivalence
   of expressions both in the arithmetic and the algebraic contexts.},
